<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Juncus oxymeris </i>and <i>J. xiphioides </i>are perennial, rhizomatous rushes. They form small stands in serpentine and nonserpentine seeps in scattered areas throughout the state. Similar falcate-leaved <i>Juncus </i>(e.g., <i>J. ensifolius </i>and <i>J. phaeocephalus</i>) also form stands in similar settings. It remains to be seen whether these ecologically and morphologically similar species constitute a single or multiple alliances. <i>J. xiphioides </i>stands appear restricted to saline and serpentine soils in California, whereas <i>J. oxymeris </i>and <i>J. phaeocephalus </i>stands occurs on several substrates. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The range of <i>Juncus oxymeris</i> includes the inner Great Valley (262A), North California Coast Ranges (M261B), Sierra Nevada (M261E), and Transverse Ranges (M262Ba-Bg). Klein et al. (2007) described stands of both <i>Juncus oxymeris</i> and <i>Juncus xiphioides</i> associations in small wetlands of the northern Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261Fa-Fb). Other stands of <i>J. phaeocephalus</i> in vernal pools at Burton Mesa Ecological Reserve (Condor Environmental Services, Inc. 2007) are along the Southern California Coast (261B). In freshwater wetlands on the Channel Islands (Junak et al. 2007), <i>J. phaeocephalus</i> shared dominance with <i>J. arcticus</i> var. <i>mexicanus</i>. The range of <i>J. xiphioide</i>s includes cismontane California and some transmontane ranges (322Al, 341Dj). Stands occur in the Central California Coast Ranges (M262Aa) at Coyote Ridge in Santa Clara Valley. They also exist along the Central California Coast (261Aa-Ad), including the San Francisco Bay estuary region in tidal marshes, sloughs, and clayey swales (Baye et al. 2000, Holstein 2000, Sycamore Associates 2001), and in the East Bay Hills at springs with <i>J. patens</i> and <i>Lolium perenne</i> (Allen-Diaz et al. 2001). </div>
</div>

	

    
